The MOST complex model APPEARED to be the BEST on the TRAINING set but... CV revealed that this model was ON AVERAGE WORSE than the INTERCEPT-ONLY or SIMPLEST possible model on NEW data!!!

Why did we need the "HACK"?¶

Or what does the penalty argument mean??

Our most COMPLEX model CONTAINS the FEATURES from the other simpler models! THe mode complex model is a SUPER SET containing all features from all other models.

But our MOST COMPLEX model has SO MANY FEATURES that it OVERFITS the training data! It memorizes the "past" and does VERY POORLY on the "future".

However, what if we could REMOVE or TURN OFF features from this most complex mode? What if we could identify the FEATURES that do NOT matter and REMOVE THEM by setting their coefficients (slopes) = 0.

This idea of using a method to FORCE coefficients to ZERO if the features does NOT matter is known as REGULARIZATION OR PENALIZATION.¶

How does this work? We fit models by MINIMIZING A LOSS. The LOSS depends on the COEFFICIENTS.

FIND the COEFFICIENTS that MINIMIZE the LOSS.

BUT REGULARIZATION modifies this approach. Instead of ONLY minimizing the LOSS, REGULARIZATION adds a PENALTY!

FIND the COEFFICIENTS that MINIMIZE the sum of the LOSS and the PENALTY.¶

If large or extreme coefficients cause the LOSS to become SMALL but also cause the PENALTY to become LARGE, then those coefficients values will NOT be identified.¶

What kind of PENALTIES exist?¶

There are many varieties of PENALTIES or REGULARIZATION approaches. We will demonstrate the 3 main types.

We will cover RIDGE, LASSO, and ELASTIC NET.

1. Ridge penalty¶

The RIDGE penalty also known as L2-norm penalty is the DEFAULT PENALTY used by LogisticRegression function. Therefore if you do NOT set penalty argument the RIDGE penalty is ASSUMED.

However, I always recommend MANUALLY setting the penalty argument so that you KNOW exactly what PENALTY you are working with!!

ALL REGULARIZATION or PENALIZATION methods include an additional PARAMETER that CONTROLS how the coefficients are estimated. LogisticRegression function names this PARAMETER C. The C parameter has DEFAULT value of 1. The C paramter MUST always have a VALUE for RIDGE!!!

But, what this means is we need to understand HOW the C parameter IMPACTS the coefficient estimates as part of the RIDGE penalty!!!

Lets try 3 different values of C on our problem for the RIDGE penalty!!!

Lets BEGIN with the DEFAULT C Parameter value for RIDGE.

VERY LARGE C values produce models similar to having NO PENALTY!!!!!!

VERY SMALL C values produce models similar to INTERCEPT-ONLY MODEL which has NO FEATURS!!!!

Essentially, the C parameter allows us to control COMPLEXITY which means the C parameter effectively GOVERNS overfitting!!!

Decreasing C will enable the COMPLEX MODEL to BEHAVE LIKE a simpler one!!!

What value of C should we use??¶

We DO NOT know!!! The C paramter is SPECIFIED by the USER!!! It controls how the COEFFICIENTS are estimated therefore it is SET BEFORE the model is FIT!!!

We MUST use Cross-Validation to TUNE the value of C. Thus, we select the value of C that MAXIMIZES the performance on NEW data on AVERAGE!!!

Cross-validation is an ESSENTIAL tool for working with regularization or penalization methods.

In [55]:
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold

The LASSO penalty FORCES the COEFFICIENTS associated with UNIMPORTANT FEATURES to be IDENTICALLY ZERO!!

The LASSO penalty therefore therefore TURNS OFF unimportant features!!

Just like the RIDGE penalty, the LASSO penalty ALSO has the C parameter. The C parameter dictates the COEFFICIENTS estimates. The IMAPCT of C is the same for LASSO and RIDGE but the LASSO penalty will literally cause unimportant features to have 0 for their coefficient.

The LASSO penalty is also known as the L1-norm so the penalty-l1 and you must change the solver="saga".

Lets try out 3 values for C to confirm the IMPACT of C on the coefficient estimates for LASSO.

Start with the DEFAULT value C=1.

3. ELASTIC NET Penalty¶

We have seen how RIDGE pushes coefficients NEAR ZERo but NEVER identically zero.

We have seen LASSO literally turn off unimportant features!!!

But which of the two methods should you use??

One approach is to TRY BOTH and use CV to identify the BETTER of the TWO!!!

In [126]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(np.log(ridge_tune.Cs_), ridge_tune.scores_[1.0].mean(axis=0), color="steelblue", label="Ridge")
ax.plot(np.log(lasso_tune.Cs_), lasso_tune.scores_[1.0].mean(axis=0), color="orange", label="Lasso")

ax.set_xlabel("log(C)")
ax.set_ylabel("Cross-Validation Accuracy")

plt.show()

HOWEVER...rather than just trying out the TWO..WHAT IF we could BLEND or MIX Lasso and Ridge together??

This is the mindset of the ELASTIC NET penalty!!! It MIXES LASSO and RIDGE to try and get the BENEFITS of BOTH!!!!

The ENET penalty ALSO has the C parameter to CONTROL how the coefficients are estimates. The C parameter IMPACT is IDENTICAL to the LASSO and RIDGE C paramter impact!!!

BUT...ENET has a SECOND TUNING parameter that must be defined!! The second tuning paramter is MIXING FRACTION between LASSO and RIDGE!!! This MIXING FRACTION is known as the l1-ratio.

Lets fit an ENET penalized model with a MIXING FRACTION of 0.5 and the DEFAULT C value.
